<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99798312286640></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99798312286640><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=6019&mid=99798312286640>RE: the haste</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=6019&mid=99798312286640#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=52206><span id= >ritualpain</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 16th 1:32 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>You're doing it wrong. The haste percentage isn't a delay reduction exactly.<br><br>For instance, FBSS is 21% haste. That will not reduce a 100 delay weapon to 79 delay though. In fact, when the formula is worked out, with FBSS a 100 delay weapon would end up being 83 delay.<br><br>Haste Formula:<br>weapon delay / (1 + [haste value/100])<br><br>example 1 (weapon is tranquil staff, haste is fbss)<br>weapon delay / (1 + [haste value/100])<br>30 / (1 + [21/100])<br>30 / 1.21<br>new delay = 24.79<br><br>example 2 (weapon is monk fists w/epic, haste is Golden Sash of Tranquility + Epic bard haste effect)<br>weapon delay / (1 + [haste value/100] + [haste value/100])<br>16 / (1+[41/100])+[40/100]<br>16 / (1.41 + 0.40)<br>16 / 1.81<br>new delay = 8.83<br>(can you say "monk epic kicks ass!"? Imagine a self hasted monk with two 9/16 weapons base, which with the golden sash of tranquility end up being 9/8.83 weapons lol. /drool<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
